<h2>Common Pairing Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

<p>The biggest mistake people make with Merlot is treating it like Cabernet Sauvignon. While both are Bordeaux varieties, Merlot's softer structure requires different pairing approaches. Avoid overly bold, heavily spiced dishes that will overwhelm the wine's subtle character.</p>

<p>Temperature matters more than many realize. Serving Merlot too warm emphasizes alcohol and diminishes fruit character. Too cold, and the wine loses its appealing softness. Find the sweet spot around 62-65°F for optimal pairing performance.</p>

<p>Another common error is choosing the wrong style for your dish. New World Merlots from warm climates work better with grilled and barbecued foods, while Old World versions complement braises and stews. Consider the wine's origin when planning your menu.</p>

<p>Don't assume all Merlots are the same. A $15 bottle from a mass producer will pair differently than a $40 estate-grown wine. The quality and style of your Merlot should match the effort and quality of your food preparation.</p>

<p>Timing your wine service with the meal prevents pairing failures. Open bottles 15-30 minutes before serving to allow the wine to breathe. This simple step improves both the wine's expression and its compatibility with food.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>What foods should I avoid with Merlot?</h3>
<p>Avoid very spicy cuisines, raw fish preparations, and dishes with overwhelming acidity like ceviche. These can clash with Merlot's moderate structure and fruit-forward character.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can I pair Merlot with seafood?</h3>
<p>Yes, but choose meatier fish preparations. Grilled salmon, tuna steaks, or seafood in rich tomato sauces work well. Avoid delicate white fish and raw preparations.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the best temperature to serve Merlot with food?</h3>
<p>Serve between 62-65°F (17-18°C). This temperature preserves the wine's fruit character while maintaining food compatibility. Too warm emphasizes alcohol; too cold mutes flavors.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How does Merlot pair with different cooking methods?</h3>
<p>Roasted and grilled preparations work best, as they develop flavors that complement Merlot's character. Braised dishes also pair well. Avoid deep-fried foods that can overwhelm the wine.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Should I decant Merlot before serving with food?</h3>
<p>Most young Merlots don't require decanting, but 30 minutes of breathing can improve integration with food. Older wines (10+ years) benefit from 60-90 minutes of decanting.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can I cook with the same Merlot I'm serving?</h3>
<p>Absolutely. Using the same wine for cooking and drinking creates harmonious pairings. Choose a bottle you'd enjoy drinking, as cooking concentrates both good and bad qualities.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do I pair Merlot with different sauce styles?</h3>
<p>Tomato-based and mushroom sauces are naturals. Cream sauces work if they're not too rich. Avoid citrus-heavy sauces that can clash with the wine's fruit character.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the difference between pairing Old World and New World Merlots?</h3>
<p>Old World Merlots (French, Italian) tend to be earthier and pair well with traditional European cuisine. New World versions are fruit-forward and complement grilled foods and bolder flavors.</p>
